results.notes:
In this case is not properly the lichen, that I think to be Parmelina tiliacea, the reason of this observation but the black dots proliferating on some zones of the thallus. Of course these could be pycnidia, which are rare in P. tiliacea, according to the British Flora.
On the other hand, these black dots are full of filiform conidia with approximate dimensions of 7 × 1 µm. Again this can be the conidia of P. tiliacea, the form being like this and a bit smaller (4.5 × 1 µm, according to the British Flora). My doubt is that the internal structure of the dots seems to be a bit complicated for pycnidia and instead it could be a lichenicolous fungus at an imperfect state. What is the best option?

Original Herbarium Label: Inocybe paludinella var. umbratica (Quél.) Gminder

Inocybe paludinella (Peck) Sacc. and Inocybe umbratica Quél. are two closely related species. Some authors (Stangl 1989, Ferrari 206) suggested that Inocybe palludinella and I. umbratica should be treated as one species. This was formally done by Gminder when he transferred I. umbratica into I. paludella as a variety: Inocybe paludinella var. umbratica (Quél.) Gminder.
This specimen (collected by Dennis Oliver) is closer to Inocybe paludinella s.str. when considering the color of the cap (yellow vs. brownish tinge), but the size of spores fits better to I. umbratica (which has slightly larger spores than those listed for I. paludinella).
WARNING: Without microscopic examination, collections of this species complex can be easily misidentified as Inocybe geophylla!

This was field IDed to Ionomidotis by Paula DeSanto (LongTooth) on the 2015 Peck Foray in Watkins Glen, NY. Microscopic features from dried material back in the SUNY ESF lab showed characters in keeping with that ID aside from the conspicuous absence of KOH extractable pigments (in 3% solution), from which the very Iono in Ionomidotis is derived. The prefix refers to a reaction by which a purplish brown pigment appears with the application of KOH, fittingly referred to as “ionomidotic.”

Authors of this Czech Mycology paper note the “indicator species” status of I. irregularis, which shows a strict preference for old growth, undisturbed forests in Europe. Assuming this is true for more than one species in the genus, and for more forests than European ones, confirming or denying the original field ID could take on new significance.
